# Milestone 03 — The CI Pipeline: Six Gates and What They Taught

**Scope:** Stage 6 of the production-readiness project — a GitHub Actions pipeline with the stages **lint → test → build → security → integration** (deploy follows in Milestone 04).

**Status at this milestone:** Every push to `main` triggers a five-gate pipeline. Each gate runs on a fresh disposable Ubuntu runner and is chained with `needs:`, so any failure freezes everything downstream. All five gates are green.

---

## 1. The mental model that everything else hangs on

### The robot inspector
Before this stage, the developer was the quality system: remembering to lint, test, rebuild, and verify. CI replaces that memory with a robot that runs the full checklist on every push, identically, forever. Passing is never a permanent status — the gate re-examines the code *as it is now* on every push, which is the point.

### Three machines
Every tool in the project lives on exactly one of three machines:
1. **The laptop** — development, editors, venvs, clutter.
2. **The runner** — a fresh, blank, disposable Ubuntu server GitHub provides per job. The inspector's workbench: tools get installed onto it, checks run on it, then the whole machine is destroyed. Nothing on it ever ships.
3. **The image** — the sealed product. Contains only what production needs at runtime.

This split resolves the dev-vs-prod dependency question permanently: fastapi/express ship in the image; pytest/fakeredis/eslint live on workbenches only (`--save-dev` in Node, separate pip installs in CI for Python; `npm ci --omit=dev` keeps them out of the image).

### The chain
`needs:` between jobs is the same idea as `depends_on: condition: service_healthy` in Compose and health-gated startup before that: **never proceed on top of something unproven.** Third appearance of the same principle, one level higher each time.

### Pipeline shape
Lint judges the **text**, test judges the **logic**, build produces the **object**, security judges the **object's contents**, integration judges the **assembled machine**. Each gate sees what the previous gates cannot. This stopped being a slogan the day the security gate caught a critical vulnerability that lint, test, and build had all waved through.

